    "remarks": {
      "sha256": "f7a565ed573ecddc863e647bd18f9e775c38401a2611f758cf8aaa4fe5e8d260",
      "source_region": "div.problem-additional-text",
      "text": "Erd\\H{o}s and Graham report they can show\\[f(n,t) \\gg \\frac{t}{\\log t}.\\]"
    },
    "statement": {
      "sha256": "0e5c4c31ac2380254aea18e908f98e59b14cca50c2695a315e8a575d5839542f",
      "source_region": "div#content",
      "text": "Let $s_t(n)$ be the $t$-smooth component of $n$ - that is, the product of all primes $p$ (with multiplicity) dividing $n$ such that $p<t$. Let $f(n,t)$ count the number of distinct possible values for $s_t(m)$ for $m\\in [n+1,n+t]$. Is it true that\\[f(n,t)\\gg t\\](uniformly, for all $t$ and $n$)?"
    }
  },
